Conceiving, then, that an object may always be regarded as placed in some one or other of these six groups of circumstances ; that is, as the subject of the sentence, as acted on directly by the subject, as acted on indirectly, as possessing, as addressed, or as subsidiary to the action; and that the several cases of the noun point out the object as inone or other of these six groups; we shall endeavour, in the following Notes, to account for the cases of nouns by referring them to one or other of the six above-mentioned general laws.
